%description:
Regression test for the D1 `installRoutes` param on ~Ted (workstream D, architecture
decoupling): with `**.ted.installRoutes = false`, Ted must stop touching the IPv4 routing
table entirely, letting another source of routes own it -- here, Ipv4NetworkConfigurator,
which is already wired up in examples/mpls/testte_failure2/RSVPTE4 -- while RSVP-TE
signaling and label-switched forwarding continue to work unaffected.

Built on the shipped examples/mpls/testte_failure2 network (RSVPTE4), which already uses
Ipv4NetworkConfigurator instead of per-node .rt files, so no rerouting/stripping of static
routes was needed -- just adding installRoutes=false and dropping its failure/recovery
scenario (irrelevant here; this test isn't about link failure).

Asserted, in order:
  1. the RSVP-TE LSP from host1 to host3 (LSR1->LSR2->LSR4->LSR5, permanent, tunnel_id 1 /
     lspid 100, per LSR1_rsvp.xml) is fully signaled -- RsvpTe::processPATH_NOTIFY's
     PATH_CREATED log line fires at the ingress once the label is actually installed;
  2. host traffic is DELIVERED end to end (packetReceived:count > 0 -- host3 runs a
     UdpEchoApp, so both directions are exercised);
  3. -- the actual point of this test -- Ted::rebuildRoutingTable() never runs on any LSR:
     with installRoutes=false, Ted logs "installRoutes=false, not touching the routing
     table" instead of ever "rebuilding routing table at", i.e. the configurator's routes
     are left untouched.

Proof that assertion 3 is a real discriminator (not a no-op check): flipping
**.ted.installRoutes back to true (the default) in this exact network config makes every
LSR log "rebuilding routing table at <routerId>" during startup/convergence (observed 49
occurrences across the 7 LSRs in a manual run) -- Ted actively deletes and reinstalls its
own /32-only route set over whatever the configurator had computed, which is exactly what
the %not-contains below guards against, so the test fails on assertion 3 as required.

Honest note on assertions 1-2: in THIS particular network (a pure point-to-point topology
with no switches/hubs), Ted's own link-state-derived Dijkstra also happens to reach every
host once flooding converges, so LSP establishment and end-to-end delivery still succeed
even with installRoutes=true (verified manually: 134-144 packets delivered either way). The
route wipe-and-reinstall is real and observable, it just doesn't happen to break
reachability in this topology -- that would require a host hidden behind a switch/hub,
which is Ted.ned's own documented "multi-access link" limitation (out of scope here, see
plans/pending workstream D). So assertion 3 is the one that actually flips PASS/FAIL
between installRoutes=false and =true; 1 and 2 are cross-checks that signaling/forwarding
are unaffected by the param either way.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = ../../../../examples;../../../../src
network = inet.examples.mpls.testte_failure2.RSVPTE4
sim-time-limit = 3s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
**.cmdenv-log-level = "info"
output-scalar-file = "${resultdir}/${configname}-#${runnumber}.sca"

**.host1.numApps = 1
**.host1.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.host1.app[0].localPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].destPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.host1.app[0].sendInterval = 0.01s
**.host1.app[0].destAddresses = "host3"

**.host3.numApps = 1
**.host3.app[0].typename = "UdpEchoApp"
**.host3.app[0].localPort = 100

**.LSR1.classifier.config = xmldoc("../../../../examples/mpls/testte_failure2/LSR1_fec.xml")
**.LSR1.rsvp.traffic = xmldoc("../../../../examples/mpls/testte_failure2/LSR1_rsvp.xml")

**.LSR*.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.LSR*.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s

**.LSR1.peers = "ppp0 ppp1"
**.LSR2.peers = "ppp0 ppp1 ppp2"
**.LSR3.peers = "ppp0 ppp1 ppp2"
**.LSR4.peers = "ppp0 ppp1 ppp2"
**.LSR5.peers = "ppp0 ppp3 ppp4"
**.LSR6.peers = "ppp0 ppp1"
**.LSR7.peers = "ppp0 ppp1"

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

*.*.hasStatus = true
# no failure scenario -- this test is about installRoutes, not link failure
**.scenarioManager.script = xml("<scenario/>")

# D1: Ted must not own the routing table here; Ipv4NetworkConfigurator does.
**.ted.installRoutes = false

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 1. the RSVP-TE LSP establishes end to end (ingress PATH_CREATED confirmation)
%contains: stdout
Path successfully established
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 2. host traffic is actually delivered over the established LSP
%postrun-command: grep "packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '$NF > 0 { print "DELIVERED", $0 }' > delivered.out
%contains: delivered.out
DELIVERED
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 3. the actual point of the test: Ted never touched the routing table
%contains: stdout
installRoutes=false, not touching the routing table
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%not-contains: stdout
rebuilding routing table at
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
